value.value: Enables the transfer of metal ions from one side of a membrane to the other.
The chemical reactions and pathways involving quinolinate, the anion of quinolinic acid, also known as 2,3-pyridinedicarboxylic acid.
Binding to an ephrin receptor.

Binding to 3,4-didehydroretinal, a form of retinal that plays a role in the visual process in freshwater fish and some amphibians analogous to that of all-trans retinal in other vertebrates. 3,4-didehydro-11-cis-retinal combines with an opsin to form cyanopsin (cone) or porphyropsin (rod).
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of saliva from a cell or a tissue.
Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of saliva.
The regulated release of hormones, substances with a specific regulatory effect on a particular organ or group of cells.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of follicle-stimulating hormone.

label.value: positive regulation of follicle-stimulating hormone secretion

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of follicle-stimulating hormone.

label.value: negative regulation of follicle-stimulating hormone secretion

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of follicle-stimulating hormone.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of a hormone from a cell.
The regulated release of follicle-stimulating hormone, a gonadotropic glycoprotein hormone secreted by the anterior pituitary.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of hormones.

label.value: positive regulation of hormone biosynthetic process

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of hormones.
Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of a hormone from a cell.
Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of a hormone from a cell.

label.value: positive regulation of lipid biosynthetic process

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of lipids.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of lipids.

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a cycloheximide stimulus. Cycloheximide (actidione) is an antibiotic produced by some Streptomyces species which interferes with protein synthesis in eukaryotes.
Catalysis of the reaction: nucleoside triphosphate + AMP = nucleoside diphosphate + ADP.
The chemical reactions and pathways involving tetrahydrofolylpolyglutamate, a folate derivative comprising tetrahydrofolate attached to a chain of glutamate residues.
The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of tetrahydrofolylpolyglutamate, a folate derivative comprising tetrahydrofolate attached to a chain of glutamate residues.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the passage or uptake of molecules by the mitochondrial membrane.
The controlled release of a substance by a cell or a tissue.
Binding to calcium oxalate, CaC2O4, a salt of oxalic acid. In animals, it may be excreted in urine or retained in the form of urinary calculi.
Catalysis of the reaction: 2 geranylgeranyl diphosphate -> 15-cis-phytoene + 2 diphosphate.

definition.value: Note that this should not be confused with 'geranylgeranyl-diphosphate geranylgeranyltransferase activity ; GO:0016767', EC:2.5.1.32. This activity is the second part of the formation of phytoene from geranylgeranyl-diphosphate, the first stage of which is catalyzed by EC:2.5.1.32.

value.value: Binding to a tetrapyrrole, a compound containing four pyrrole nuclei variously substituted and linked to each other through carbons at the alpha position.
The directed movement of substances within a cell.
Binds to and stops, prevents or reduces the activity of pectinesterase.

definition.value: See also the molecular function term 'pectinesterase activity ; GO:0030599'.

value.value: The formation of bonds from two or more atoms within the same ligand to a metal atom in complexes in which the metal is part of a ring.

label.value: acyltransferase activity, acyl groups converted into alkyl on transfer

value.value: Catalysis of the transfer of an acyl group from one compound (donor) to another (acceptor), with the acyl group being converted into alkyl on transfer.

Binding to a transition metal ions; a transition metal is an element whose atom has an incomplete d-subshell of extranuclear electrons, or which gives rise to a cation or cations with an incomplete d-subshell. Transition metals often have more than one valency state. Biologically relevant transition metals include vanadium, manganese, iron, copper, cobalt, nickel, molybdenum and silver.

label.value: transition metal ion transmembrane transporter activity

value.value: Enables the transfer of transition metal ions from one side of a membrane to the other. A transition metal is an element whose atom has an incomplete d-subshell of extranuclear electrons, or which gives rise to a cation or cations with an incomplete d-subshell. Transition metals often have more than one valency state. Biologically relevant transition metals include vanadium, manganese, iron, copper, cobalt, nickel, molybdenum and silver.
Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + 3-dephospho-CoA = 2'-(5''-triphosphoribosyl)-3'-dephospho-CoA + adenine.
Catalysis of the transfer of a pyruvyl (oxopropanoyl) group from one compound to another.
Catalysis of the transfer of an L-fucosyl group from GDP-beta-L-fucose to an acceptor molecule to form an alpha-(1->3) linkage.
Catalysis of the transfer of an L-fucosyl group from GDP-beta-L-fucose to an acceptor molecule to form an alpha-(1->6) linkage.
Catalysis of the transfer of an alpha-L-fucosyl residue from GDP- beta-L-fucose to the serine hydroxy group of a protein acceptor.
Binding to an endoplasmic reticulum (ER) retention sequence, a specific peptide sequence that ensures a protein is retained within the ER.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of a neurotransmitter from a cell.
Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the regulated release of a neurotransmitter.
A protein complex providing a discrete opening in a membrane that allows the passage of gases and/or liquids.
The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a pore complex. A pore complex is a small opening in a membrane that allows the passage of liquids and/or gases.

definition.value: See also the cellular component term 'pore complex ; GO:0046930'.

label.value: sodium-transporting ATP synthase activity, rotational mechanism

value.value: Enables the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction: ADP + phosphate + Na+(out) => ATP + H2O + Na+(in), by a rotational mechanism.

label.value: proton-transporting ATP synthase activity, rotational mechanism

value.value: Enables the synthesis of ATP from ADP and phosphate by the transfer of protons from one side of a membrane to the other by a rotational mechanism driven by a gradient according to the reaction: ADP + H2O + phosphate + H+(in) -> ATP + H+(out).
Catalysis of the reaction: a 1-phosphatidyl-1D-myo-inositol 4,5-bisphosphate + ATP = a 1-phosphatidyl-1D-myo-inositol 3,4,5-trisphosphate + ADP + H+.
Modulates the activity of the enzyme 1-phosphatidylinositol-3-kinase activity.

definition.value: See also the molecular function term '1-phosphatidylinositol-3-kinase activity ; GO:0016303'.

value.value: Catalysis of the reaction: 2'-deoxyadenosine + H+ + H2O = 2'-deoxyinosine + NH4+.

The chemical reactions and pathways involving phytochelatins, any of a group of peptides that bind metals (Cd, Zn, Cu, Pb, Hg) in thiolate coordination complexes. The structure is of the type (gamma-glutamyl-cysteinyl)n-glycine, where n is 2 to 11.

The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of phytochelatins, any of a group of peptides that bind metals (Cd, Zn, Cu, Pb, Hg) in thiolate coordination complexes. The structure is of the type (gamma-glutamyl-cysteinyl)n-glycine, where n is 2 to 11.
